The '''Epistle of Eugnostos''' is one of many [[Gnostic]] tractates from the [[Nag Hammadi library]], discovered in [[Egypt]] in 1945. The Nag Hammadi codices contain two full copies of this tractate. The [[epistle]] was a familiar literary convention of Antiquity; it is not to be supposed that this essay is an actual letter written by a man named ''Eugnostos'' ("right thinking", sometimes Eugnostus).

The text is devoid of any specifically Christian themes or associations, and simply describes the esoteric cosmology of the gnostics. The similarity with the cosmology in ''[[The Sophia of Jesus Christ|Sophia of Jesus Christ]]'' led [[Douglas M. Parrott]] to conclude that that work was an adaption of this Epistle for a Christian audience. Parrott places the two side by side for comparison  in his translation for ''The Nag Hammadi Library in English'', edited by Robinson.<ref>Parrott, Douglas, translation and introduction of "Eugnostos the Blessed" and "The Sophia of Jesus Christ" in ''The Nag Hammadi Library'', James Robinson, editor. 1990:220-243</ref>

